<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE5AFFE4FF3FF656FA9549EE" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE5AFFE4FF3FF656FEDD487E" blockId="4.[189,335,1033,1059]" box="[189,335,1033,1059]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE5AFFE4FF3FF656FEDD487E" bold="true" box="[189,335,1033,1059]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FF3FF656FEDD487E" bold="true" box="[189,335,1033,1059]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE5AFFE4FF3FF667FA9549EE" blockId="4.[188,1401,1080,1459]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">
Colonies erect, biserial, with rectilinear or slightly curved, narrow branches, triangular in crosssection. Autozooids distinct, alternating in two rows on either side of median keel, rectangular, slightly asymmetrical, abrupt inclination from median keel, separated by shallow grooves, distal edge slightly raised (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE5AFFE4FEFAF6FDFE4B48E1" box="[376,473,1186,1212]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-106@3.[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Canda ukirensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 431). A. Frontal view of the colony showing different autozooids, avicularia and vibracula. B. Dorsal view of the colony showing vibracular pores. C. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids. D. Close-up of dorsal view of the colony showing vibracula with setal grooves and vibracular pores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580788/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Gymnocyst absent. Cryptocyst slightly granular, asymmetrically developed, extended more distally on outer side (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE5AFFE4FDFBF69AFD464882" box="[633,724,1221,1247]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-106@3.[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Canda ukirensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 431). A. Frontal view of the colony showing different autozooids, avicularia and vibracula. B. Dorsal view of the colony showing vibracular pores. C. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids. D. Close-up of dorsal view of the colony showing vibracula with setal grooves and vibracular pores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580788/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
, uppermost zooid). Large communication pores visible in distolateral corners, emplaced on broad immersed shelf of each autozooid. Opesia large, oval, tapering proximally. Scutum lacking. Avicularia placed laterally along central axis, sessile, broad and about half as long as zooid, each zooid producing single avicularium occupying its inner distal half, rostrum obliquely positioned with respect to colony surface and long axis (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE5AFFE4FC40F70DFB8F4931" box="[962,1053,1362,1388]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-106@3.[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Canda ukirensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 431). A. Frontal view of the colony showing different autozooids, avicularia and vibracula. B. Dorsal view of the colony showing vibracular pores. C. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids. D. Close-up of dorsal view of the colony showing vibracula with setal grooves and vibracular pores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580788/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). The dorsal side occupied by vibracula with long, curved, deep setal groove, oriented distolaterally; shallow crisscross median furrow corresponds to zooidal boundaries. Radicular pore very large (
<figureCitation id="130C2CF3DE5AFFE4FC15F7C7FB8549EE" box="[919,1047,1432,1459]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-106@3.[189,1398,1119,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Canda ukirensis sp. nov., holotype (GIS/B 431). A. Frontal view of the colony showing different autozooids, avicularia and vibracula. B. Dorsal view of the colony showing vibracular pores. C. Enlargement of the colony showing autozooids. D. Close-up of dorsal view of the colony showing vibracula with setal grooves and vibracular pores." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6580788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6580788/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Fig. 2B, D</figureCitation>
). Ooecium not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32D63FDDE5AFFE4FF3FF785FBE34B60" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B883076DE5AFFE4FF3FF785FEA249A9" blockId="4.[189,304,1498,1524]" box="[189,304,1498,1524]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">
<heading id="D0C0871ADE5AFFE4FF3FF785FEA249A9" bold="true" box="[189,304,1498,1524]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FF3FF785FEA249A9" bold="true" box="[189,304,1498,1524]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B883076DE5AFFE4FF3FF457FBE34B60" blockId="4.[187,1399,1544,1853]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FF3FF457FDCD4A7E" authority="(Pourtales, 1867)" baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[189,607,1544,1571]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="retiformis">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FF3FF457FE1A4A7F" box="[189,392,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Canda retiformis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FE1BF457FDC44A7E" author="Pourtales L. F." box="[409,598,1544,1571]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="103 - 120" refId="ref8145" refString="Pourtales L. F. 1867. Contributions to the fauna of the Gulf Stream at great depths. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College in Cambridge 1: 103 - 120." type="journal article" year="1867">Pourtalès, 1867</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the north pacific recent species has resemblance with 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FB6BF456FAE44A7F" authority="Sonar &amp; Pawar &amp; Wayal, 2022" authorityName="Sonar &amp; Pawar &amp; Wayal" authorityYear="2022" box="[1257,1398,1544,1571]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="ukirensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FB6BF456FAE44A7F" box="[1257,1398,1544,1571]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">C. ukirensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A270511FDE5AFFE4FF3FF473FE8E4A1B" box="[189,284,1580,1606]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in broad sessile avicularia but differs in the depressed cryptocyst and presence of scutum. 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FF3FF411FD8A4A34" authority="Thornely, 1907" authorityName="Thornely" authorityYear="1907" box="[189,536,1614,1641]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="pecten">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FF3FF411FEF24A35" box="[189,352,1614,1640]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Canda pecten</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FEE4F411FD8A4A34" author="Thornely L. R." box="[358,536,1614,1641]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="179 - 196" refId="ref8725" refString="Thornely L. R. 1907. Report on the marine Polyzoa in the collection of the Indian Museum. Records of the Indian Museum 1: 179 - 196." type="journal article" year="1907">Thornely, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FDD6F411FCBB4A34" author="Tilbrook K. J." box="[596,809,1614,1641]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="1 - 386" refId="ref8799" refString="Tilbrook K. J. 2006. Cheilostomatous Bryozoa from the Solomon Islands. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs 4 (Studies in Biodiversity) 3: 1 - 386." type="journal article" year="2006">Tilbrook 2006: 54</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 8c) differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FB94F410FB314A35" authority="Sonar &amp; Pawar &amp; Wayal, 2022" authorityName="Sonar &amp; Pawar &amp; Wayal" authorityYear="2022" box="[1046,1187,1614,1641]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="ukirensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FB94F410FB314A35" box="[1046,1187,1614,1641]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">C. ukirensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A270511FDE5AFFE4FB2BF410FA914A34" box="[1193,1283,1615,1641]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having triangular opesia and large frontal avicularia above branch bifurcation. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FBA5F42DFAE44AD1" author="Di Martino E. &amp; Taylor P. D." box="[1063,1398,1650,1676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="17 - 126" refId="ref7167" refString="Di Martino E. &amp; Taylor P. D. 2014. Miocene Bryozoa from East Kalimantan, Indonesia. Part 1: Cyclostomata and ' Anascan' Cheilostomata. Scripta Geologica 146: 17 - 126." type="journal article" year="2014">Di Martino &amp; Taylor, 2014</bibRefCitation>
studied the Indonesian Cenozoic species 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FD27F4CAFCAF4AF2" box="[677,829,1685,1711]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="federiciae">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FD27F4CAFCAF4AF2" box="[677,829,1685,1711]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">C. federiciae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FCFAF4CAFC6A4AF2" authorityName="Di Martino &amp; Taylor" authorityYear="2014" box="[888,1016,1685,1711]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="giorgioi">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FCFAF4CAFC6A4AF2" box="[888,1016,1685,1711]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">C. giorgioi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which differ from 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FB61F4CAFAFD4AF2" authorityName="Sonar &amp; Pawar &amp; Wayal" authorityYear="2022" box="[1251,1391,1685,1711]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="ukirensis">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FB61F4CAFAFD4AF2" box="[1251,1391,1685,1711]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">C. ukirensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: the former in the absence of avicularia and the latter in the absence of avicularia, raised distal autozooidal edges and egg-shaped opesia. The Recent species 
<taxonomicName id="4C374BF5DE5AFFE4FCA0F484FB324AAB" authority="(Harmer, 1926)" baseAuthorityName="Harmer" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[802,1184,1755,1782]" class="Gymnolaemata" family="Candidae" genus="Canda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cheilostomatida" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="foliifera">
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FCA0F484FC4E4AA8" box="[802,988,1755,1781]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Canda foliifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FC6DF484FB0A4AAB" author="Harmer S. F." box="[1007,1176,1755,1782]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="183 - 501" refId="ref7913" refString="Harmer S. F. 1926. The Polyzoa of the Siboga Expedition, 2. Cheilostomata Anasca. Siboga Expedition Reports 28 b: 183 - 501." type="journal article" year="1926">Harmer, 1926</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F32070E6DE5AFFE4FB6CF484FAD64AA8" box="[1262,1348,1755,1781]" name="Taiwan" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
has some resemblance in general morphology to the Kachchh species but it has a more extensive granular cryptocyst with a straight proximal edge (see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA64D87DE5AFFE4FD57F57DFC7C4B61" author="Gluhak T. &amp; Lewis J. E. &amp; Popijac A." box="[725,1006,1826,1852]" pageId="4" pageNumber="20" pagination="397 - 426" refId="ref7204" refString="Gluhak T., Lewis J. E. &amp; Popijac A. 2007. Bryozoan fauna of Green Island, Taiwan: First indications of biodiversity. Zoological Studies 46: 397 - 426." type="journal article" year="2007">
Gluhak 
<emphasis id="B943EC64DE5AFFE4FCB0F57CFCF44B61" box="[818,870,1826,1852]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="20">et al</emphasis>
. 2007: 403
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 7a–d).
</paragraph>
